== Historical Accounts == In the ''Nihon Shoki,'' Tanba Michinushi no Mikoto was sent to Tanba Province in the 10th year of Emperor Sujin’s reign as one of the Four Commanders of the Four Roads. Alongside other commanders such as {{ill|Ōhiko-no-Mikoto|ja|大彦命|1=Ōhiko-no-Mikoto|1=Ōhiko-no-Mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōhiko-no-Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōhiko-no-Mikoto|qq=}}, {{ill|Takeshi Uchino Sukune|ja|武渟川別|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeshi Uchino Sukune|qq=}}, and {{ill|Kibitsuhiko no Mikoto|ja|吉備津彦命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kibitsuhiko no Mikoto|qq=}}, he was instrumental in pacifying the region.{{Sfn|丹波道主命（古代氏族）|2010th year |p=426}}
The ''Kojiki,'' however, attributes the expedition to his father, Hikoiimasu no Mikoto, and offers no further details about his activities.
== Burial == Although the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Household Agency|qq=}} has not designated an official burial site for Tanba Michinushi no Mikoto, the {{ill|Kumobe Kofun|ja|雲部車塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumobe Kofun|qq=}} in {{ill|Sasayama, Hyōgo|ja|丹波篠山市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sasayama, Hyōgo|qq=}} is traditionally associated with him. This keyhole-shaped tomb, the largest in the Tanba region, is about 140 meters long.{{Sfn|事典陵墓参考地|2005th year |p=49}}
